Panel Discussion

Main Auditorium LG001, Cass Business School, City University London

Organizer: Dr. Elena Novelli, Cass Business School, ESRC Future Research Leaders Fellow

Event funded by the ESRC Future Research Leaders Grant

#scaleandscope

Technological change has led to an explosive increase in connectivity and reach. Globalization, open innovation, crowdsourcing, interconnected systems have all become common phenomena. Thousands of start-ups have emerged from all over the world and across all sectors with novel ways of doing business. In parallel, incumbent companies have changed. Some have grown considerably (e.g. Amazon, Google, Microsoft, Apple), sometimes integrating their suppliers or their complementors and gaining direct access to their customers. Other companies have instead shrunk and increased their open collaboration, outsourcing or partnership practices. Some firms have even emerged as &amp;quot;virtual corporations&amp;quot;. These patterns raise many questions for managers and policy makers. How important are the size of a company and its degree of diversification to succeed in today's world? What could be the most successful competitive strategies for startups and large companies, respectively? Has technological change marked the end or the resurgence of the large corporations? What are some of the ways that companies are using technology to modify their scope and business model, using technological innovation to enhance their productivity, i.e. doing in-house what they outsourced and vice versa?

