In line with the spirit of fostering the diffusion of results from my research to the user community, in 2016 I have co-founded and started serving as the co-Director of the Digital Leadership Research Centre at Cass Business School (DLRC). In the same year I have started delivering sessions based on my research results to a target audience of entrepreneurs and executives. For example I have delivered a session titled &amp;quot;From Ideas to Reality: Capturing Value from Technological Innovation&amp;quot; at City Unrulyversity, targeted to the entrepreneurial community of Tech City.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2016</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>4B06F81C-C51A-4A4F-B842-722FDE559D6C</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>56dda9babc2580.62664328</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Published article on Research Policy on the antecedents and implications of patent scope. Synthesis appeared on ESRC Britain in 2016:
&amp;quot;Every year inventing firms invest their money to file thousands of patents that in principle provide their inventors with temporary monopolies on the use of their ideas in return for disclosing them to the public. The 'scope' of a patent, i.e. the area that it covers, is supposed to reflect the protection that the patent provides to its holder. But what are we precisely referring to when we talk about &amp;quot;patent scope&amp;quot; and to what extent a larger scope actually provides superior protection to the patent owner? Research conducted by Elena Novelli at Cass Business School focused on US patents developed by inventing firms delves deeper into this issue and suggests that patent claims and patent technological classification should be considered jointly to determine the actual 'size' of patent scope.
An inventing firm wants to avoid that another firm comes up with a small change to the original idea and calls it a new invention. Hence it will describe all possible changes to the original idea in the patent itself, so that those changes will be covered by the patent protection. These variations to the original idea are described in the patent 'claims'. A higher number of claims increases the strength of patent protection because it is a deterrent to other inventors from building on the knowledge underlying the focal patent, as they entail a higher risk of infringement. The changes described in the claims can be very marginal variations to the invention -e.g. they can refer to changes in the diameter of a component- or more 'distant' -e.g. they may refer to completely different materials from which the same component could be made. They can even refer to different technological domains - for instance textile, metal working, liquid crystals. Previous research has commonly assumed that patents that have their claims spread across many technological classes confer stronger protection to the inventing firm because they extend the protection of the patent across different technological settings.
However this is not necessarily the case. If the claims are too dispersed across technological domains the protection they provide can actually be relatively lower. When an inventing firm identifies a change to the invention and publishes it in the patent it is actually suggesting to the public how that invention could be used in another technological domain, opening up a possible new trajectory of development for the idea. But the inventing firm itself might not be in the position to exploit this trajectory and this might end up giving an advantage to other parties. For instance, patents with claims classified in more different classes have greater visibility and are more likely to 'cross' more firms' search processes. Yet, it is less likely that the focal firm has the capabilities to develop the patent along so many directions. Moreover, it may be difficult for the inventing firm to detect possible infringements across multiple technological areas. Research by Elena Novelli shows empirically that, holding constant the number of patent claims, when they refer to very distant technological classes, other firms (rather than the inventing firm itself) tend to generate patents that build on the firm's original invention - patents that in principle could rather have been developed by the focal firm itself. Moreover, this research also shows that the characteristics of firms' knowledge and experience are factors associated to firms' ability to develop patents with a broader or narrower scope.&amp;quot;

Developed additional six working papers (at different points of the review process), addressing the following questions:

-What are the best strategies to exploit the potential fungibility of firms' ideas and resources? Under what conditions are more fungible technologies better exploited via direct entry versus in strategic factor markets? 

- Which scale and scope configurations enable firms to appropriate more value from their resources?

-Under what conditions should firms reconfigure their resources in response to the emergence of a new business model? 

-How does complexity of the firm product portfolio (number of elements and interdependencies between them) and the change in interdependencies affect firm performance?
&amp;nbsp;
-Under what conditions should firms invest in interdependent markets? 

